{"title_page": "Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation\n| logo                = Welcome logo VOC Logo Words Navy copy.png\n| type                = Non-profit\n| tax_id              = 52-1920858\n| founded_date        = 1994\n| founders            = {{unbulleted list|[[Lee Edwards]]|[[Lev Dobriansky]]|[[Zbigniew Brzezinski]]<ref name=NYT1993/>}}\n| location            = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| origins             = \n| key_people          = {{unbulleted list|[[Lee Edwards]], Chairman| [[Aldona Wos]], Vice Chairman|Marion Smith, Executive Director<ref name =jac>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/jun/17/museum-honor-victims-communism-seek-spot-national-/|title=Cold War Casualties of Communism Seek Museum on National Mall|publisher=The Washington Times|first=Jacqueline |last=Kilmas|date=June 17, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>}}\n| focus               = Anti-communism; human rights, Pro-capitalism\n| revenue             = \n| endowment           = \n| num_volunteers      = \n| num_employees       = \n| num_members         = \n| homepage            = http://www.victimsofcommunism.org\n}}\n\nThe '''Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation''' is a non-profit anti-communist organization in the [[United States]], authorized by a unanimous [[Act of Congress]] in 1993 for the purpose of \"educating Americans about the ideology, history and legacy of [[communism]]\".<ref name=ATL>{{cite news | last=Rauch | first=Jonathan | work=[[The Atlantic]] | date=December 2003 | title=The Forgotten Millions | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200312/rauch | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> The foundation was responsible for building the [[Victims of Communism Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] It is a member of the European Union's [[Platform of European Memory and Conscience]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1991, Senator [[Steve Symms]] and Representative [[Dana Rohrabacher]] introduced concurring resolutions in the [[United States Congress]] urging the construction of \"an International Memorial to the Victims of Communism at an appropriate location within the boundaries of the District of Columbia and for the appointment of a commission to oversee the design, construction and all other pertinent details of the memorial.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=S. Con. Res. 55 | work=thomas.loc.gov | publisher=Library of Congress | url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c102:S.CON.RES.55: | accessdate=November 5, 2009| date=July 26, 1991 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=H. Con. Res. 228 | work=thomas.loc.gov | publisher=Library of Congress | url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c102:H.CON.RES.228: | accessdate=November 5, 2009| year=1991 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Rohrabacher and Senator [[Jesse Helms]] sponsored [[Amend (motion)|amendments]] to The [[FRIENDSHIP Act of 1993]] which authorized such construction.<ref>{{cite news | work=The New York Times | title=U.S. Laws Catch Up to the New Russia | date=November 29, 1993 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/29/us/us-laws-catch-up-to-the-new-russia.html | accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref> The Act was signed into law by [[Bill Clinton|President Bill Clinton]] on December 17, 1993.<ref>{{cite web | title=Bill Summary and Status | work=thomas.loc.gov | publisher=Library of Congress | url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d103:h.r.03000: | accessdate=November 5, 2009| date=December 17, 1993 }}</ref> The Act cited \"the deaths of over 100,000,000 victims in an unprecedented imperial holocaust,\" and resolved that \"the sacrifices of these victims should be permanently memorialized so that never again will nations and peoples allow so evil a tyranny to terrorize the world.\"<ref name=ATL/> The 100 million victim number is taken from the controversial ''[[The Black Book of Communism|Black Book of Communism]],'' often criticized for inflating numbers to reach the 100 million mark<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Torpey|first=John|date=2001-01-01|title=What future for the future? reflections on The Black Book of Communism|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s12142-001-1028-0|journal=Human Rights Review|language=en|volume=2|issue=2|pages=135\u2013143|doi=10.1007/s12142-001-1028-0|issn=1874-6306}}</ref>.\n\n[[File:Goddess of Democracy DC defy censorship.JPG|thumb|left|The [[Victims of Communism Memorial]]. The statue is a recreation by Thomas Marsh of the \"Goddess of Democracy\", which was destroyed in [[Tiananmen Square]] by the government of the [[People's Republic of China]]]]\nAccording to Title IX, Section 905 of Public Law 103-199, an independent organization was to be established to construct, maintain and operate the [[Victims of Communism Memorial]] in Washington, D.C., as well as to collect the contributions for the establishment of the memorial and to encourage the participation of all groups suffered under communism.<ref name=s905>[http://www.mega.nu/ampp/pl103-199.html Public Law 103-199]</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the foundation completed the Victims of Communism Memorial, which was dedicated by [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]].<ref name =reuters>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-usa-communism-idUSPEK20924820070614|title=China Blasts Bush Tribute to Victims of Communism|publisher=Reuters|date=June 13, 2007|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince March 2014 Marion Smith serves as Executive Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/issues/marion-smith-joins-victims-of-communism-memorial-foundation/|title=Marion Smith Joins Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|date=2014-03-05|website=Washington Free Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Foundation released a list of 51 [[prisoners of conscience]] in Cuba just before President [[Barack Obama|Barack Obama's]] visit and meeting with [[Ra\u00fal Castro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4266636/cuba-political-prisoners-castro/|title=Advocates List Cuba's Political Prisoners After Castro Says There Are None|publisher=Time|first=Maya |last=Rhodan |date=March 21, 2016 |access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the foundation released a report calling attention to [[Organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners in China|organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners and Uyghurs in China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lipes|first=Joshua|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/uyghur/organs-03122020163712.html|title=Uyghur, Falun Gong Detainees Likely Source For China's Organ Market: Report|date=March 12, 2020|work=[[Radio Free Asia]]|access-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Programs==\n\n===Victims of Communism Memorial===\nThe memorial was dedicated on June 12, 2007 \u2014 the 20th anniversary of [[Ronald Reagan|President Ronald Reagan]]'s \"[[Tear down this wall]]\" speech in [[Berlin]]. The unveiling of the statue in Washington DC earned international press attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kommersant.com/p-10890/r_530/Communist_deaths/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010005710/http://www.kommersant.com/p-10890/r_530/Communist_deaths/|title=Bush Blames 100 Million Deaths on Communists |publisher=Kommersant |date= June 13, 2007| access-date=May 18, 2016|archive-date=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe land was a gift of the US Parks Service, and the remaining cost, over $1 million, was raised from private sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/a-tale-of-two-monuments-washington-vs-ottawa|title=A tale of Two Monuments: Washington vs. Ottawa|publisher=Ottawa Citizen |first=Don |last=Butler|date=March 6, 2015|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref> Sculpted by Thomas Marsh, it is a 10-foot bronze replica of the [[Papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]] Goddess of Democracy statue made by student democracy protesters leading up to the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square massacre]] in 1989.<ref name=NR2>{{cite news | work=The National Review | last=Miller | first=John | date=December 12, 2005 | title=Memorial Day: Honoring the victims of Communism | url=http://www.nationalreview.com/miller/miller200512120846.asp | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Museum===\nThe foundation aims to build a museum in Washington, D.C.<ref name=NYT1993>{{cite news | work=[[The New York Times]] | last=Smith | first=Dinitia | title=For the Victims of Communism | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/23/arts/for-the-victims-of-communism.html | date=December 23, 1995 | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> The foundation is working on a proposed budget for a museum near the [[National Mall]], and has received a $1 million grant toward the museum from the government of [[Hungary]].<ref name =jac/> Plans for the museum include exhibit space, an auditorium, archives, and resident scholars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/first-a-memorial-then-a-museum/article/819714|title=First a Memorial, Then a Museum|publisher=The Weekly Standard|first=Jonathan |last=Last|date=December 1, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/08/25/communism-s-victims-deserve-a-museum.html|title=Communism's Victims Deserve a Museum|newspaper=The Daily Beast|first=James|last=Kirchick|date=August 25, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom===\nThe Foundation annually presents its Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom at an event which honors opponents of communism, and has been used to raise funds for the construction of the memorial.<ref name=\"Clyne\">{{cite news | work=[[The New York Sun]] | last=Clyne | first=Meghan | title=D.C. Monument To Be Built In Honor of Victims of Communism | date=December 13, 2005 | url=http://www.nysun.com/national/dc-monument-to-be-built-in-honor-of-victims/24366/ | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> Past recipients include [[Myroslav Marynovych]], [[Chen Guangcheng]], [[Tom Lantos]], [[Pope John Paul II]], [[Vaclav Havel]], [[Yang Jianli]], [[Fr. Nguyen Van Ly]], [[Yelena Bonner]], [[William F. Buckley, Jr]].,\n[[Richard Pipes]], [[Guillermo Fari\u00f1as]], [[Lane Kirkland]], [[Armando Valladares]], [[J\u00e1nos Horv\u00e1th]], [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]], [[Anna Walentynowicz]], [[National Endowment for Democracy]], and [[Henry M. Jackson|Henry \"Scoop\" Jackson]].<ref name=\"Clyne\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/383611/sweet-solidarity-part-ii-jay-nordlinger|title=Sweet Solidarity, Part II|publisher=National Review|first=Jay |last=Nordlinger|date=July 25, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://victimsofcommunism.org/initiative/truman-reagan/|title=Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom |publisher=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://atimes.com/2015/11/chinese-dissident-receives-political-award-in-washington/|title=Chinese Dissident Receives Political Award in Washington|publisher=Asia Times|date=November 16, 2015|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/remembering-yesterdays-victims-of-communism-and-todays/|title=Feature: Chinese dissident Yang Jianli awarded Reagan-Truman Medal of Freedom at sixth anniversary of Victims of Communism Memorial|last=McMorris|first=Bill|date=2013-06-14|website=Washington Free Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Projects===\nIn 2015, the foundation released a biopic video series called Witness Project, featuring interviews with witnesses of communism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philanthropydaily.com/what-about-communism/%7C|title=What About Communism|publisher=Philanthropy Daily|author=Abigail Clevenger|date= May 8, 2014|access-date=May 24, 2016}}</ref> Other projects include national seminars for high-school teachers and for college campuses<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/52-1920858|title=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation Programs|website=www.guidestar.org|access-date=2019-08-02}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== China and Covid-19 ===\nIn April 2020 the Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation chose to include all victims of the Covid-19 outbreak as \"victims of communism\" and blamed the Chinese government for every single death accross the globe. However, organisation's statements contain no reference to any other factors including lack of access to sick leave in America, anti-lockdown protests, late respinses and lack of PPE in many countries outside of China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.victimsofcommunism.org/voc-news/2020/4/5/blame-the-chinese-communist-party-for-the-coronavirus-crisis|title=Blame the Chinese Communist Party for the Coronavirus Crisis|website=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailycaller.com/2020/04/10/communism-china-coronavirus-deaths/|title=Victims Of Communism Memorial Foundation Adds Global Coronavirus Deaths To Its Tally Of Historical Victims Of Communism|website=dailycaller.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n<br />\n== People ==\n[[File:Lee Edwards publicity shot.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Chairman Lee Edwards]]\n\nThe chairman is [[Lee Edwards]]. Its chairman emeritus was [[Lev Dobriansky]] (deceased). The national advisory council includes [[Dennis DeConcini]], [[Paul Hollander]], [[John K. Singlaub]], [[John Earl Haynes]], and [[George Weigel]]. Former (deceased) members include [[Robert Conquest]], [[Richard Pipes]], [[Rudolph Rummel]], and [[Jack Kemp]].<ref name=advisory>{{cite web|url=http://victimsofcommunism.org/mission/board-advisory-councils/|title=Board & Advisory Councils|publisher=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|access-date=May 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325203039/http://victimsofcommunism.org/mission/board-advisory-councils/|archive-date=March 25, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe international advisory council includes [[Sali Berisha]], [[Vladimir Bukovsky]], [[Emil Constantinescu]], [[Mart Laar]], [[Vytautas Landsbergis]], [[Guntis Ulmanis]], [[Armando Valladares]], and [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa|Lech Walesa]]. Former members include [[Yelena Bonner]], [[Brian Crozier]], [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d G\u00f6ncz]], and [[V\u00e1clav Havel]].<ref name=advisory/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Memorial (society)]]\n*[[Museum of Communism, Czech Republic]]\n*[[Museum of Communism, Warsaw]]\n*[[Virtual Museum of Soviet Repression in Belarus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Victims Of Communism Memorial Foundation}}\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Civic and political organizations of the United States]]\n[[Category:Foundations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Educational foundations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Commemoration of communist crimes]]\n[[Category:Conservative political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Democracy promotion]]\n[[Category:Human rights organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation\n| logo                = Welcome logo VOC Logo Words Navy copy.png\n| type                = Non-profit\n| tax_id              = 52-1920858\n| founded_date        = 1994\n| founders            = {{unbulleted list|[[Lee Edwards]]|[[Lev Dobriansky]]|[[Zbigniew Brzezinski]]<ref name=NYT1993/>}}\n| location            = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| origins             = \n| key_people          = {{unbulleted list|[[Lee Edwards]], Chairman| [[Aldona Wos]], Vice Chairman|Marion Smith, Executive Director<ref name =jac>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/jun/17/museum-honor-victims-communism-seek-spot-national-/|title=Cold War Casualties of Communism Seek Museum on National Mall|publisher=The Washington Times|first=Jacqueline |last=Kilmas|date=June 17, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>}}\n| focus               = Anti-communism; human rights, Pro-capitalism\n| revenue             = \n| endowment           = \n| num_volunteers      = \n| num_employees       = \n| num_members         = \n| homepage            = http://www.victimsofcommunism.org\n}}\n\nThe '''Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation''' is a non-profit anti-communist organization in the [[United States]], authorized by a unanimous [[Act of Congress]] in 1993 for the purpose of \"educating Americans about the ideology, history and legacy of [[communism]]\".<ref name=ATL>{{cite news | last=Rauch | first=Jonathan | work=[[The Atlantic]] | date=December 2003 | title=The Forgotten Millions | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200312/rauch | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> The foundation was responsible for building the [[Victims of Communism Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] It is a member of the European Union's [[Platform of European Memory and Conscience]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1991, Senator [[Steve Symms]] and Representative [[Dana Rohrabacher]] introduced concurring resolutions in the [[United States Congress]] urging the construction of \"an International Memorial to the Victims of Communism at an appropriate location within the boundaries of the District of Columbia and for the appointment of a commission to oversee the design, construction and all other pertinent details of the memorial.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=S. Con. Res. 55 | work=thomas.loc.gov | publisher=Library of Congress | url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c102:S.CON.RES.55: | accessdate=November 5, 2009| date=July 26, 1991 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=H. Con. Res. 228 | work=thomas.loc.gov | publisher=Library of Congress | url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c102:H.CON.RES.228: | accessdate=November 5, 2009| year=1991 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Rohrabacher and Senator [[Jesse Helms]] sponsored [[Amend (motion)|amendments]] to The [[FRIENDSHIP Act of 1993]] which authorized such construction.<ref>{{cite news | work=The New York Times | title=U.S. Laws Catch Up to the New Russia | date=November 29, 1993 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/29/us/us-laws-catch-up-to-the-new-russia.html | accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref> The Act was signed into law by [[Bill Clinton|President Bill Clinton]] on December 17, 1993.<ref>{{cite web | title=Bill Summary and Status | work=thomas.loc.gov | publisher=Library of Congress | url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d103:h.r.03000: | accessdate=November 5, 2009| date=December 17, 1993 }}</ref> The Act cited \"the deaths of over 100,000,000 victims in an unprecedented imperial holocaust,\" and resolved that \"the sacrifices of these victims should be permanently memorialized so that never again will nations and peoples allow so evil a tyranny to terrorize the world.\"<ref name=ATL/> The 100 million victim number is taken from the controversial ''[[The Black Book of Communism|Black Book of Communism]],'' often criticized for inflating numbers to reach the 100 million mark<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Torpey|first=John|date=2001-01-01|title=What future for the future? reflections on The Black Book of Communism|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s12142-001-1028-0|journal=Human Rights Review|language=en|volume=2|issue=2|pages=135\u2013143|doi=10.1007/s12142-001-1028-0|issn=1874-6306}}</ref>.\n\n[[File:Goddess of Democracy DC defy censorship.JPG|thumb|left|The [[Victims of Communism Memorial]]. The statue is a recreation by Thomas Marsh of the \"Goddess of Democracy\", which was destroyed in [[Tiananmen Square]] by the government of the [[People's Republic of China]]]]\nAccording to Title IX, Section 905 of Public Law 103-199, an independent organization was to be established to construct, maintain and operate the [[Victims of Communism Memorial]] in Washington, D.C., as well as to collect the contributions for the establishment of the memorial and to encourage the participation of all groups suffered under communism.<ref name=s905>[http://www.mega.nu/ampp/pl103-199.html Public Law 103-199]</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the foundation completed the Victims of Communism Memorial, which was dedicated by [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]].<ref name =reuters>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-usa-communism-idUSPEK20924820070614|title=China Blasts Bush Tribute to Victims of Communism|publisher=Reuters|date=June 13, 2007|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince March 2014 Marion Smith serves as Executive Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/issues/marion-smith-joins-victims-of-communism-memorial-foundation/|title=Marion Smith Joins Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|date=2014-03-05|website=Washington Free Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Foundation released a list of 51 [[prisoners of conscience]] in Cuba just before President [[Barack Obama|Barack Obama's]] visit and meeting with [[Ra\u00fal Castro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4266636/cuba-political-prisoners-castro/|title=Advocates List Cuba's Political Prisoners After Castro Says There Are None|publisher=Time|first=Maya |last=Rhodan |date=March 21, 2016 |access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the foundation released a report calling attention to [[Organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners in China|organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners and Uyghurs in China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lipes|first=Joshua|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/uyghur/organs-03122020163712.html|title=Uyghur, Falun Gong Detainees Likely Source For China's Organ Market: Report|date=March 12, 2020|work=[[Radio Free Asia]]|access-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the organization announced they will be adding the global victims of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Covid-19 outbreak]] to their death toll of communism, blaming the Chinese government for the outbreak and every death caused by it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.victimsofcommunism.org/voc-news/2020/4/5/blame-the-chinese-communist-party-for-the-coronavirus-crisis|title=Blame the Chinese Communist Party for the Coronavirus Crisis|website=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailycaller.com/2020/04/10/communism-china-coronavirus-deaths/|title=Victims Of Communism Memorial Foundation Adds Global Coronavirus Deaths To Its Tally Of Historical Victims Of Communism|website=dailycaller.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\n\n===Victims of Communism Memorial===\nThe memorial was dedicated on June 12, 2007 \u2014 the 20th anniversary of [[Ronald Reagan|President Ronald Reagan]]'s \"[[Tear down this wall]]\" speech in [[Berlin]]. The unveiling of the statue in Washington DC earned international press attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kommersant.com/p-10890/r_530/Communist_deaths/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010005710/http://www.kommersant.com/p-10890/r_530/Communist_deaths/|title=Bush Blames 100 Million Deaths on Communists |publisher=Kommersant |date= June 13, 2007| access-date=May 18, 2016|archive-date=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe land was a gift of the US Parks Service, and the remaining cost, over $1 million, was raised from private sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/a-tale-of-two-monuments-washington-vs-ottawa|title=A tale of Two Monuments: Washington vs. Ottawa|publisher=Ottawa Citizen |first=Don |last=Butler|date=March 6, 2015|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref> Sculpted by Thomas Marsh, it is a 10-foot bronze replica of the [[Papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]] Goddess of Democracy statue made by student democracy protesters leading up to the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square massacre]] in 1989.<ref name=NR2>{{cite news | work=The National Review | last=Miller | first=John | date=December 12, 2005 | title=Memorial Day: Honoring the victims of Communism | url=http://www.nationalreview.com/miller/miller200512120846.asp | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Museum===\nThe foundation aims to build a museum in Washington, D.C.<ref name=NYT1993>{{cite news | work=[[The New York Times]] | last=Smith | first=Dinitia | title=For the Victims of Communism | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/23/arts/for-the-victims-of-communism.html | date=December 23, 1995 | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> The foundation is working on a proposed budget for a museum near the [[National Mall]], and has received a $1 million grant toward the museum from the government of [[Hungary]].<ref name =jac/> Plans for the museum include exhibit space, an auditorium, archives, and resident scholars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/first-a-memorial-then-a-museum/article/819714|title=First a Memorial, Then a Museum|publisher=The Weekly Standard|first=Jonathan |last=Last|date=December 1, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/08/25/communism-s-victims-deserve-a-museum.html|title=Communism's Victims Deserve a Museum|newspaper=The Daily Beast|first=James|last=Kirchick|date=August 25, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom===\nThe Foundation annually presents its Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom at an event which honors opponents of communism, and has been used to raise funds for the construction of the memorial.<ref name=\"Clyne\">{{cite news | work=[[The New York Sun]] | last=Clyne | first=Meghan | title=D.C. Monument To Be Built In Honor of Victims of Communism | date=December 13, 2005 | url=http://www.nysun.com/national/dc-monument-to-be-built-in-honor-of-victims/24366/ | accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> Past recipients include [[Myroslav Marynovych]], [[Chen Guangcheng]], [[Tom Lantos]], [[Pope John Paul II]], [[Vaclav Havel]], [[Yang Jianli]], [[Fr. Nguyen Van Ly]], [[Yelena Bonner]], [[William F. Buckley, Jr]].,\n[[Richard Pipes]], [[Guillermo Fari\u00f1as]], [[Lane Kirkland]], [[Armando Valladares]], [[J\u00e1nos Horv\u00e1th]], [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]], [[Anna Walentynowicz]], [[National Endowment for Democracy]], and [[Henry M. Jackson|Henry \"Scoop\" Jackson]].<ref name=\"Clyne\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/383611/sweet-solidarity-part-ii-jay-nordlinger|title=Sweet Solidarity, Part II|publisher=National Review|first=Jay |last=Nordlinger|date=July 25, 2014|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://victimsofcommunism.org/initiative/truman-reagan/|title=Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom |publisher=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://atimes.com/2015/11/chinese-dissident-receives-political-award-in-washington/|title=Chinese Dissident Receives Political Award in Washington|publisher=Asia Times|date=November 16, 2015|access-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/remembering-yesterdays-victims-of-communism-and-todays/|title=Feature: Chinese dissident Yang Jianli awarded Reagan-Truman Medal of Freedom at sixth anniversary of Victims of Communism Memorial|last=McMorris|first=Bill|date=2013-06-14|website=Washington Free Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Projects===\nIn 2015, the foundation released a biopic video series called Witness Project, featuring interviews with witnesses of communism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philanthropydaily.com/what-about-communism/%7C|title=What About Communism|publisher=Philanthropy Daily|author=Abigail Clevenger|date= May 8, 2014|access-date=May 24, 2016}}</ref> Other projects include national seminars for high-school teachers and for college campuses<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/52-1920858|title=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation Programs|website=www.guidestar.org|access-date=2019-08-02}}</ref>\n\n== People ==\n[[File:Lee Edwards publicity shot.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Chairman Lee Edwards]]\n\nThe chairman is [[Lee Edwards]]. Its chairman emeritus was [[Lev Dobriansky]] (deceased). The national advisory council includes [[Dennis DeConcini]], [[Paul Hollander]], [[John K. Singlaub]], [[John Earl Haynes]], and [[George Weigel]]. Former (deceased) members include [[Robert Conquest]], [[Richard Pipes]], [[Rudolph Rummel]], and [[Jack Kemp]].<ref name=advisory>{{cite web|url=http://victimsofcommunism.org/mission/board-advisory-councils/|title=Board & Advisory Councils|publisher=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|access-date=May 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325203039/http://victimsofcommunism.org/mission/board-advisory-councils/|archive-date=March 25, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe international advisory council includes [[Sali Berisha]], [[Vladimir Bukovsky]], [[Emil Constantinescu]], [[Mart Laar]], [[Vytautas Landsbergis]], [[Guntis Ulmanis]], [[Armando Valladares]], and [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa|Lech Walesa]]. Former members include [[Yelena Bonner]], [[Brian Crozier]], [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d G\u00f6ncz]], and [[V\u00e1clav Havel]].<ref name=advisory/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Memorial (society)]]\n*[[Museum of Communism, Czech Republic]]\n*[[Museum of Communism, Warsaw]]\n*[[Virtual Museum of Soviet Repression in Belarus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Victims Of Communism Memorial Foundation}}\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Civic and political organizations of the United States]]\n[[Category:Foundations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Educational foundations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Commemoration of communist crimes]]\n[[Category:Conservative political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Democracy promotion]]\n[[Category:Human rights organizations]]\n", "name_user": "BulgeUwU", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victims_of_Communism_Memorial_Foundation"}
